				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \alpha = \frac{1}{d}In\left[ {\frac{1 - R}{T}} \right] $$\end{document}
where, T is the measured transmittance, R is the measured reflectance and d is the thickness of the deposited films.

The RBS film thickness is determined from the energy loss of the projectile He + ions. It can also be estimated from the total number of counts of the signal (the peak area). The film thickness t is related to the energy difference ΔE (i.e. the energy width of the RBS signal) between the ions scattered from the front surface (KE0; where E0 is the primary energy and K is the kinetic factor) and those from the rear surface (E1,t) of the film (i.e. from the film surface and those from the film-substrate or film-film interface) by the following formula [30]:3ΔE=KE0-El,t=ε¯Nt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
